now we move to version 3: automated certificate rotation with alerting. This is production-grade, so you never lose access to your cluster. I’ll break it down carefully for a beginner, line by line.
Step 0 — Directory Layout

mkdir -p ~/k8s-users/certs
mkdir -p ~/k8s-users/kubeconfigs
cd ~/k8s-users

Explanation:

~/k8s-users/certs → store keys and certs
~/k8s-users/kubeconfigs → store separate kubeconfigs per user
Keeps things clean and organized

Step 1 — Production Script

Save as create-k8s-user-v2.sh:

#!/bin/bash
# Usage: ./create-k8s-user-v2.sh <username> <group> <namespace>

USERNAME=$1
GROUP=$2
NAMESPACE=$3

if [ -z "$USERNAME" ] || [ -z "$GROUP" ] || [ -z "$NAMESPACE" ]; then
  echo "Usage: $0 <username> <group> <namespace>"
  exit 1
fi

echo "🔑 Creating Kubernetes user: $USERNAME in group $GROUP"

CERT_DIR=certs/$USERNAME
KUBECONFIG_DIR=kubeconfigs
mkdir -p $CERT_DIR

# Step 1️⃣: Generate private key
openssl genrsa -out $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.key 2048
echo "✅ Private key generated: $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.key"

# Step 2️⃣: Generate CSR
openssl req -new -key $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.key -out $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.csr -subj "/CN=${USERNAME}/O=${GROUP}"
echo "✅ CSR generated: $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.csr"

# Step 3️⃣: Encode CSR in base64 for Kubernetes
CSR_BASE64=$(cat $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.csr | base64 | tr -d '\n')

# Step 4️⃣: Create Kubernetes CSR YAML
cat <<EOF > $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}-csr.yaml
apiVersion: certificates.k8s.io/v1
kind: CertificateSigningRequest
metadata:
  name: ${USERNAME}-csr
spec:
  request: ${CSR_BASE64}
  signerName: kubernetes.io/kube-apiserver-client
  expirationSeconds: 86400
  usages:
    - client auth
EOF

kubectl apply -f $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}-csr.yaml
echo "📄 CSR applied to Kubernetes: $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}-csr.yaml"

# Step 5️⃣: Approve CSR
kubectl certificate approve ${USERNAME}-csr
echo "✔️ CSR approved for user: $USERNAME"

# Step 6️⃣: Extract signed certificate
kubectl get csr ${USERNAME}-csr -o jsonpath='{.status.certificate}' | base64 -d > $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.crt
echo "📄 Signed certificate saved: $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.crt"

# Step 7️⃣: Create per-user kubeconfig
USER_KUBECONFIG=$KUBECONFIG_DIR/${USERNAME}-kubeconfig
kubectl config set-cluster default-cluster \
  --server=$(kubectl config view -o jsonpath='{.clusters[0].cluster.server}') \
  --certificate-authority=$(kubectl config view -o jsonpath='{.clusters[0].cluster.certificate-authority}') \
  --embed-certs=true \
  --kubeconfig=$USER_KUBECONFIG

kubectl config set-credentials $USERNAME \
  --client-certificate=$CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.crt \
  --client-key=$CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.key \
  --embed-certs=true \
  --kubeconfig=$USER_KUBECONFIG

kubectl config set-context ${USERNAME}-context \
  --cluster=default-cluster \
  --user=$USERNAME \
  --namespace=$NAMESPACE \
  --kubeconfig=$USER_KUBECONFIG

kubectl config use-context ${USERNAME}-context --kubeconfig=$USER_KUBECONFIG

echo "🎉 Kubeconfig created for user: $USER_KUBECONFIG"

# Optional: Auto backup
tar czf $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}-backup-$(date +%F).tgz $CERT_DIR
echo "💾 Backup created: $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}-backup-$(date +%F).tgz"

Step 2 — How it works

| Step | What it does        | Explanation for beginners                 |
| ---- | ------------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| 1    | Generate key        | Your secret key, don’t share              |
| 2    | Generate CSR        | Request form for Kubernetes               |
| 3    | Base64 encode       | Kubernetes needs CSR in one line          |
| 4    | Create YAML         | Official request for cluster approval     |
| 5    | Apply CSR           | Send to Kubernetes                        |
| 6    | Approve CSR         | Kubernetes signs the certificate          |
| 7    | Extract certificate | Now you have your login cert              |
| 8    | Create kubeconfig   | Separate file per user                    |
| 9    | Backup              | Saves certs + key in a compressed archive |

Step 3 — Run the script

chmod +x create-k8s-user-v2.sh
./create-k8s-user-v2.sh dahir dev-group default

